Oct 10 2009 	Very nice hotel with excellent service.	Service was the best feature at the Marriott Union Square. While checking in (early), I asked for a quiet room and was moved to an &quot;interior&quot; room. I ended up in an alcove at the end of the hall, overlooking an adjacent rooftop. Even there, the view was fine. More importantly, it was very quiet. I heard almost no hall noise or street noise nor did I hear any TV from adjacent rooms. It was quite impressive for a center-city location.I also got excellent recommendations for a quick lunch and sushi dinner that were within a short walk. BART was also an easy walk. The location isn't especially unique--there are many downtown hotels in downtown SF.I was most impressed with the desk staff helping another guest check in. The woman behind the desk was patient and calm while the guest was stressed. Within the time it took me to print my boarding pass, they solved the problem to the guests delight.Cleanliness was excellent throughout. Also, the rooms have many of the most modern amenities, including panel to connect electronics to the wide screen TV, lots of convenient outlets for recharging, an MP3-ready clock radio, and an ethernet cable ready on the desk (no in-room wireless). Like most hotels in its category, there is a modest fee for internet connectivity.Kudos for the dual flush toilets.The hotel wasn't &quot;perfect&quot;, but it was solid. The imperfections: I couldn't find a pool, but that was not a bid deal for me. My young daughter would probably have been bored here, but it was a solid business hotel, probably a 10 minute walk to the convention center. There is no Starbucks in the hotel, but there is one across the street and one about every other block around SF, so it wasn't a problem getting caffeine in the morning.	
