Jan 13 2006	Just PERFECT!!	Booked two rooms when staying in San Francisco for a friend's birthday treat. I travel a lot on business - this hotel exceeded my expectations. It was one of the best decisions of the trip. I split the holiday between two hotels in the city and really regretted leaving the Crowne Plaza.(1) LocationAn easy walk from the Powell Street BART station (I took the BART from the airport). Great for shopping, being two blocks from Union Square. Great for all the city-centre attractions. The cable-car stops outside reception! Takes you down to Powell / Market Street, or down to Fishermans Wharf.(2) RoomsWe had a standard room. Quality and cleanliness very high. Most rooms seem to have a large bay window. My room was at the back of the hotel and I could see the bay and quite a lot of the city, including Coit Tower and the Transamerica Pyramid. The bay window is great. The room is bigger as a result and you get a much wider view from your hotel. The beds are very comfortable. Every room has a CD player and they even provide a relaxing &quot;sleep-advantage&quot; CD.(3) Food / FacilitiesDidn't try the restaurant - so many choices in San Fran!!The breakfast was great (Crowne Plaza's usual standard). There is also a coffee-shop / Deli in the hotel that does fantastic egg &amp; bacon breakfast muffins - dangerous!! Lot's of coffee choices, bagels, muffins, cereals etc - I recommend it for a faster getaway in the morning. There is a friendly bar. We were also given vouchers on arrival that gave you a free drink in the bar and concessions at the restaurant etc.	
Dec 9 2005 	Great location great service small room	I was in SF on business and this was one of the few places that had the number of nights I needed, six, and was close to the Moscone Center. I was able to get a corporate rate of $130 plus tax for each night.The staff service was excellent. The bell captains helped me with a ride to the airport and were exceptional in their service, the housekeeping staff helped me with some laundry, the housekeeping staff kept my room neat and tidy, the wake-up service actually came to check on me when I was unable to get to the phone to answer the wake-up call, etc. This place had better staff service than grander hotels where I have stayed.The room was smaller than some other rooms I've had, but it had a king-sized bed, a chair and ottoman, a desk, and a dresser. The TV was set on on a stand that wasn't in front of the bed, so it was uncomfortable to watch. My room gave me a view of Powell Street and I could hear the cable car bell occasionally, but overall, being on the 10th floor, the street sound wasn't bad; the only time it woke me up was when sirens were going by. The sleep kit they give you is really, really nice; I am a light sleeper, so this was very much appreciated.The bath products are very nice. Herbal and spa like. It was one of the better lines I've had in hotels; even nicer than the Parc 55, where I stayed a year ago.The location is great. There's a 24-hour Walgreens across the street, lots of casual restaurants nearby, a short walk to Union Square, a 10-minute walk to the Moscone Center, a short walk to Chinatown, a Wells Fargo machine nearby, etc. The location is far superior to the Parc 55, the only other SF hotel I've visited.The drapes had a stain on them, and the carpet seemed old and musty, but otherwise, the room was furnished nicely. The bed linens seemed very clean, including the duvet cover, which is important to all travelers.The hotel has a Cafe Fresco, which has great hours and a nice selection of foods to go, as well as some seating. For a business traveller, like myself, this was great.My one complaint is that I could smell food smells one night. I don't know if a neighboring room had room service or if the smell came in from the heating and cooling units. It was gross though. There was no way to open the window to air out my room.If I return to SF next December, I might stay there again, but I might try another hotel just to try something different.	
Nov 30 2005 	Big room great bed no exec club breakfast	Enjoying a large, clean room near Union Square without paying a fortune is a rarity in San Francisco. The new bedding and the &quot;sleep kit&quot; amenity really did help me sleep better in this lively city. The staff were very courteous and helpful. Usually I have access to the executive club breakfast room in Intercontinental Hotels, but they didn't have one here.... instead I went across the street to an authentic European cafe. The lobby of the hotel is small and busy; perhaps the elevators are not monitored as closely as they should be for people wandering in off the street. Overall, I was pleased and would return.	
Oct 31 2005	Very pleased with this coice of hotel!	A friend and I were looking to stay in the Union Square area for the Nike Women's Marathon, and we were extremely pleased with this hotel for several reasons:1. LOCATION, LOCATION, LOCATION - a few blocks up the hill from the BART station, one block from Union Square stores and the race expo, catty-corner from a 24-hr Walgreens (which I made several trips to!), right by cable car stop, and many cafes/coffee shops/restaurants to choose from. I ended up hitting a great but cheap Thai place called Bangkok on Powell twice in 3 days. We were also about a mile walk from the Ferry Bldg.2. Quasi-known quantity - we did a lot of internet research and tried to find a swanky or funky boutique hotel that met all our criteria but the most promising ones either didn't have double beds or the TripAdvisor feedback warned me off. I figured if we did have a problem, I'd have better luck resolving issues with a corporate hotel like CP than an independent place. Plus I knew I liked the new CP bedding.3. Great rate - due to luck, I was able to get my company's corporate rate, which put the CP rate significantly lower than comparable hotels in the area.This obviously won't help out most of you, but if you work for a big company with your own Travel Services, try to see if there is a corporate rate. Bonus: the sales dept had delivered to our room a little bag of Mrs. Fields cookies and a note greeting me as a visitor from my company, which was not expected but a nice extra touch.The hotel was very nice - nothing over the top luxurious, but I don't need the 5-star treatment, nor do I care to pay for it. Lobby area was small-ish but not too important to me. The room (2 dbl beds) was above avg in size, with an addl sitting area in the bay window and desk with dataport (no issue w/ the high-speed internet connection speed). Overall, I got a killer corporate rate ($130 + tax) for an above-avg hotel in a fabulous location.	
